Introduction

This analysis uses AI to compare the median per year for various IMF metrics of CFA franc zone countries to non-CFA franc zone African countries in the Western and Middle Africa region. The purpose of this analysis is to challenge the claim that the CFA franc zone promotes growth and development. It’s important to note that this analysis does not suggest that the CFA franc is the sole cause of underdevelopment in these countries.

The countries in the CFA franc zone for this analysis are:

WAEMU

  • Benin
  • Burkina Faso
  • Côte d’Ivoire
  • Mali
  • Niger
  • Senegal
  • Togo
  • Guinea Bissau

CEMAC

  • Cameroon
  • Congo
  • Gabon
  • Equatorial Guinea
  • Central African Republic
  • Chad

The non-CFA franc zone countries for this analysis are the countries in the West Africa and Middle Africa region not in the WAEMU or the CEMAC.

West Africa:

  • Cabo Verde
  • The Gambia
  • Ghana
  • Guinea
  • Liberia
  • Mauritania
  • Sierra Leone
  • Nigeria

Middle Africa:

  • São Tomé and Príncipe
  • Angola
  • The Democratic Republic of the Congo

Guinea-Bissau joined the WAEMU in 1997, Mali joined the WAEMU in 1984 and Equatorial Guinea joined the CEMAC in 1985, so any metrics before the year a country joined is considered non-CFA franc zone and any metrics equal to or greater than the year a country joined the CFA franc zone is considered CFA franc zone.

The Comoros is ommited from this analysis, it is part of the East Africa region and uses the Comorian Franc.

Disclaimer

I created the graphs for each IMF metric. The text below the graphs, labeled “Definition of {indicator}” and “Comparing Median Intervals for indicator {indicator},” is generated by ChatGPT 3.5 using this prompt. The purpose of the prompt is to provide a definition for each indicator and then draw a conclusion comparing the the CFA franc zone and non-CFA franc zone countries based on count in which the median was greater across the yearly intervals for the given indicator. For example, if non-CFA countries had a higher median GDP 18 times out of the 22 yearly intervals between 1980 and 2022, the prompt will draw a conclusion based on that count.

The graphs presented in the “Analysis” section support my challenge to the idea that the CFA franc zone is beneficial for economic growth and development. The graphs in the appendix are additional ones I created from the same IMF data source with the same prompt.

CFA Franc Zone

The CFA franc, originally the French African Colonial franc, was created in 1945 and imposed on France’s colonies. The CFA franc zone of today is an area of monetary cooperation, comprised of two African economic zones: the West Africa Economic and Monetary Union (WAEMU) and the Central African Economic and Monetary Union (CEMAC), along with Comoros. It should be noted that since 1993, the two CFA francs and the Comorian franc cannot be exchanged for one another. To exchange one currency for the other, it must first be converted to euros. This additional step in conversion creates additional demand for euros, which consequently acts as a privileged intermediary in trade between the African countries. Overall, more than 162 million people use the two CFA francs.

Key decisions concerning the CFA franc zone are made in Paris. The central actor in this system is the French Treasury. All foreign exchange transactions (the purchase or sale of CFA francs) of the 15 countries in the franc zone must go through the French Treasury due to the French guarantee of unlimited convertibility of CFA francs into euros. This makes France the only country in the world that directly manages a set of currencies distinct from its own.

The CFA franc zone is based on four interrelated principles: the fixed exchange rate, the free movement of capital, the free convertibility of the currency, and the centralization of foreign exchange reserves.

Supporters of the CFA franc system suggest that it provides monetary stability, economic attractiveness, investment inflows, and an increase in the growth rate.

The idea that the CFA franc promotes growth and development has been widely touted by the Bank of France. In 2015, the Bank of France stated, “For over forty years, the franc zone has been an instrument of solidarity and development aimed at consolidating growth, reducing poverty, and deepening regional integration.” Additionally, in 2012, Christian Noyer, the governor of the Bank of France, remarked, “The last fifty years have shown that the franc zone is a favorable factor for development.”

However, the CFA franc zone has four major downsides for the countries that are part of it: an excessively rigid exchange rate regime, a problematic pegging to the euro, the underfinancing of African economies, and a free movement of capital that generates a massive financial bleed-out.

GDP Per Capita, Current Prices comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of GDP Per Capita, Current Prices

Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita, measured in U.S. dollars, is a crucial indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It reflects the average value of final goods and services produced within a country over a specified period, divided by the average population for the same year. By considering GDP per capita at current prices, we obtain a comprehensive understanding of a nation’s economic activity, taking into account both the volume of production and the prevailing prices. This measure allows us to gauge the standard of living and economic progress, as it considers population growth alongside economic output. Hence, GDP per capita at current prices is a fundamental tool for comparing and analyzing the economic performances of different countries, aiding policymakers in making informed decisions regarding economic development and welfare improvement.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator GDP Per Capita, Current Prices

A higher GDP per capita, measured in current prices, plays a crucial role in promoting economic growth and development. It signifies an increase in the value of final goods and services produced per person and reflects the overall productivity and efficiency of a country’s economy. In the case of non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, compared to CFA franc zone countries, there have been more yearly intervals from 1980 to 2023 with a higher median GDP per capita at current prices. This suggests a potential advantage for non-CFA middle/west Africa countries in terms of economic output and standard of living. However, to gain deeper insights into the comparative performance between the two groups, a more comprehensive analysis is required, considering factors such as population dynamics, resource availability, and policy frameworks.

Definition of GDP Per Capita, Current Prices

GDP per capita, measured in purchasing power parity (PPP) international dollars, is an essential indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. This metric enables a comprehensive understanding of the average economic well-being experienced by individuals within a nation. By evaluating the total value of goods and services produced in a country, adjusted for price differences across countries, GDP per capita in PPP terms reflects the real purchasing power of individuals in that country. This measure proves significant for comparing living standards and economic performance across nations, as it accounts for disparities in price levels and exchange rates, thus providing a more accurate representation of economic development and income distribution. Such insights into a country’s economic growth and prosperity can help policymakers formulate effective strategies to address socio-economic challenges and enhance the overall welfare of their respective populations.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator GDP Per Capita, Current Prices

It signifies a higher average income and reflects the overall economic activity within a country. This implies that these non-CFA middle/west Africa countries experienced more consistent economic growth and development, as reflected in their higher average income levels. Such a comparative insight emphasizes the potential impact of currency arrangements, such as the CFA franc, on economic performance and highlights the importance of macroeconomic policies and monetary frameworks in supporting sustained economic progress.

Implied PPP Conversion Rate comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Implied PPP Conversion Rate

The concept of Implied PPP Conversion Rate, measured in national currency per international dollar, is a valuable indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It provides insight into the relative price levels between countries and reflects the purchasing power of domestic currency in comparison to the international currency. By comparing the implied PPP conversion rates of different countries, policymakers and economists can assess the competitiveness of domestic industries, identify potential trade imbalances, and evaluate the overall economic health of a nation. This measure is particularly important in understanding the relative standards of living, the cost of goods and services, and the potential for arbitrage opportunities across countries.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Implied PPP Conversion Rate

A higher Implied PPP Conversion Rate can potentially promote economic growth and development by enhancing a country’s competitiveness and attracting foreign investments. It indicates that the national currency has a higher purchasing power in relation to the international currency, which can lead to lower import costs and increased domestic consumption. However, it is important to note that a higher Implied PPP Conversion Rate alone is not sufficient for sustainable economic growth. Other factors such as productivity, infrastructure development, and efficient institutional frameworks also play crucial roles. When comparing the Implied PPP Conversion Rates between CFA franc zone countries and non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, it is evident that CFA franc zone countries have generally exhibited higher medians over the years. This suggests that, in terms of relative price levels and purchasing power, CFA franc zone countries may have had a more favorable and stable economic environment. However, it is essential to consider various other economic indicators to gain a comprehensive understanding of the overall economic performance and development of these countries.

Current Account Balance comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Current Account Balance

The concept of Current Account Balance, measured in Billions of U.S. dollars, is a crucial indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It encompasses various transactions in a country’s balance of payments, including exports and imports of goods and services, payments of income, and current transfers between residents and nonresidents. A positive current account balance implies that the country is a net lender to the rest of the world, indicating that it is exporting more than it is importing and receiving more income from abroad than it is paying out. This surplus can contribute to economic growth and development, as it indicates competitiveness in global trade, attracts foreign investment, and allows for domestic savings and investments. Conversely, a negative current account balance signifies that the country is a net borrower from the rest of the world, indicating a trade deficit and higher foreign obligations. This deficit can affect economic growth and development, as it may require borrowing or selling of assets to finance the shortfall, potentially leading to a buildup of external debt and reduced economic stability. Hence, monitoring and managing the current account balance is crucial for policymakers to ensure sustainable economic growth and development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Current Account Balance

A higher Current Account Balance can indeed promote economic growth and development. It signifies that a country is exporting more than it is importing, which can boost domestic industries, create employment opportunities, and enhance productivity. This surplus allows the country to accumulate savings, attract foreign investment, and invest in infrastructure and human capital. In the case of non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, when analyzing the yearly intervals from 1980 to 2023, there appears to be a higher median in their Current Account Balance compared to CFA franc zone countries. This observation suggests that non-CFA middle/west Africa countries have potentially experienced better trade performance, which can be beneficial for their economic growth and development. However, a comprehensive analysis considering other factors such as fiscal policy, government effectiveness, and domestic structural characteristics would be necessary to provide a more precise comparative insight between the two regions.

Primary Net Lending/Borrowing comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Primary Net Lending/Borrowing

The concept of Primary Net Lending/Borrowing (% of GDP) refers to the difference between a country’s non-interest government revenue and its total expenditure, expressed as a percentage of its Gross Domestic Product (GDP). This indicator plays a significant role in assessing a country’s economic growth and development due to several reasons. Firstly, it reflects the sustainability of a government’s fiscal policy. A positive primary balance implies that a government is generating surplus funds, indicating prudent fiscal management and the ability to allocate resources towards investments that spur economic growth. On the other hand, a negative primary balance signals that a country is borrowing to fund its expenditures, potentially indicating fiscal stress and the potential crowding-out of private investments. Secondly, this indicator provides insights into a country’s capacity to service its debt. A higher primary surplus suggests a greater ability to meet interest obligations, potentially enhancing investors’ confidence and lowering borrowing costs. Conversely, a negative primary balance may raise concerns about a country’s ability to manage its debt burden, affecting financial stability and economic prospects. Overall, Primary Net Lending/Borrowing (% of GDP) acts as a crucial gauge of a nation’s economic performance and sustainability by reflecting its fiscal prudence, debt servicing capacity, and potential future growth prospects.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Primary Net Lending/Borrowing

A higher Primary Net Lending/Borrowing can potentially promote economic growth and development, according to the Keynesian perspective. Keynesian economists argue that during periods of economic downturns or insufficient private sector spending, government intervention through fiscal policies can stimulate aggregate demand and boost economic activity. Through borrowing or increasing net lending, governments can inject funds into the economy, either through increased government expenditure or tax cuts, which can create a multiplier effect, leading to increased consumption, investment, and overall economic growth. However, it is important to note that the impact of Primary Net Lending/Borrowing on economic growth and development can vary depending on various factors, such as the efficiency of government spending, the nature of investments made, and the overall macroeconomic conditions. Regarding Primary Net Lending/Borrowing between the CFA Franc zone countries and non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, a comparative insight can be drawn. Non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, with relatively higher Primary Net Lending/Borrowing over the years, may have had more opportunities for government intervention and fiscal stimulus to promote economic growth and development. Conversely, CFA Franc zone countries, with the fixed exchange rate regime and limited fiscal policy autonomy, may face constraints in utilizing Primary Net Lending/Borrowing as a tool to drive economic growth. However, it is essential to consider other factors such as trade dynamics, structural policies, and institutional quality to provide a comprehensive assessment of the economic performance and development of these regions.

Real GDP Growth Rate, per capita comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Real GDP Growth Rate, per capita

The Real GDP Growth Rate, measured as a percentage change in per capita, represents the annualized rate at which a country’s total output of goods and services, adjusted for inflation, is expanding or contracting. It serves as a key indicator of a nation’s economic growth and development. A higher Real GDP Growth Rate implies increased productivity and economic prosperity, as it reflects the ability to produce and consume more goods and services per person over time. This, in turn, enhances living standards, lowers unemployment rates, and creates a positive environment for investment, fostering long-term economic stability. Conversely, a lower or negative Real GDP Growth Rate signifies economic challenges, such as recessions or stagnant growth, which can lead to job losses, income inequalities, and reduced public welfare. Monitoring and analyzing Real GDP Growth Rate per capita is therefore crucial for policymakers and economists alike, enabling them to identify trends, design appropriate policies, and support sustainable economic progress.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Real GDP Growth Rate, per capita

A higher Real GDP Growth Rate, per capita, is generally seen as a driver of economic growth and development. It signifies increased production and consumption of goods and services per person, reflecting improved living standards, employment opportunities, and investment prospects. Analyzing the Real GDP Growth Rate, per capita, between non-CFA middle/west Africa countries and CFA franc zone countries from 2004 to 2023 reveals that non-CFA middle/west African countries had more yearly intervals with a higher median. This indicates that, on average, non-CFA middle/west African countries experienced more sustained economic growth and development compared to their CFA franc zone counterparts during this period. However, further examination would be necessary to comprehensively understand the drivers behind these variances, which may include factors such as monetary policy, exchange rate dynamics, governance, and structural characteristics of their economies.

Net Foreign Direct Investment comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Net Foreign Direct Investment

Net Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) as a percentage of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is a measure of the amount of inflow or outflow of FDI relative to the total economic output of a country. This indicator holds great significance in assessing a nation’s economic growth and development. A higher ratio of Net FDI to GDP suggests that a country is attracting a substantial inflow of FDI, which can fuel economic expansion, technological advancements, and employment opportunities. Moreover, an increased FDI inflow may encourage the transfer of managerial expertise and know-how, fostering productivity gains and capacity building. It also indicates the level of confidence that foreign investors place in a country’s economy, policies, and prospects. However, FDI as a percentage of GDP should not be viewed as the sole determinant of economic development, but rather as one among many indicators that informs policymakers and economists about a country’s attractiveness to foreign investors and its potential for sustained growth.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Net Foreign Direct Investment

A higher level of Net Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) can indeed promote economic growth and development. It can bring in new capital, technology, expertise, and employment opportunities, which are crucial drivers of productivity and output expansion. In the case of non-CFA middle/west African countries, there appears to be a higher median Net FDI as a percentage of GDP in comparison to the CFA franc zone countries between 2004 and 2023. This suggests that non-CFA middle/west African countries have attracted a relatively greater level of foreign investment on average, which could potentially contribute to their economic growth and development. However, it is important to note that evaluating the impact of FDI on economic growth requires a comprehensive analysis that considers other factors such as domestic policies, institutions, infrastructure, and market conditions.

Conclusion

In conclusion, non-CFA Middle Africa and West Africa countries consistently had a higher median GDP per capita than CFA franc zone countries and a higher median real GDP growth rate, which tends to be one of the conventional ways to compare economic development between countries. CFA franc zone countries also had a higher median implied PPP conversion rates, suggesting that the currency is overvalued. This overvaluation is expected since both CFA francs in the CFA franc zone are pegged to the euro. An overvalued currency has the effect of making CFA franc zone exports less competitive, thus leading to fewer exports which can hinder the development of domestic production and the domestic economy. This claim is further supported by the consistently higher median of non-CFA countries to CFA franc zone countries when considering the metrics exports of goods and services and overall current account balances. In addition, non-CFA franc zone countries also had much higher levels of net foreign direct investment. This could be in part that their economies are able to attract more net investment and/or non-CFA countries don’t have the same levels of capital flight that CFA franc zone countries have due to the free movement of capital. This ultimately reinforces the challenge to the claim that the CFA franc zone promotes economic growth.

Definition of Real GDP Growth Rate

Real GDP Growth Rate, expressed as a percentage change, is a crucial indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It reflects the annual rate at which the total value of final goods and services produced within a country, adjusted for inflation, has increased or decreased. This measure allows policymakers and economists to evaluate the health and trajectory of an economy, aiding in the formulation of informed policies and strategies. Sustained positive real GDP growth is desirable as it signifies increasing economic output, job creation, and improved standards of living. It is indicative of a country’s ability to meet the needs and aspirations of its citizens and lays the foundation for long-term sustainable development. Conversely, negative or stagnant growth rates suggest an underperforming economy, which may indicate inefficiencies, insufficient investment, or structural constraints that impede progress. Consequently, monitoring the real GDP growth rate serves as an invaluable tool in assessing economic performance and informing policy decisions aimed at fostering growth and development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Real GDP Growth Rate

A higher Real GDP Growth Rate promotes economic growth and development by indicating an expansion of an economy’s output over time. In the context of non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, when comparing Real GDP Growth Rates between these countries and CFA franc zone countries from 1980 to 2023, there appears to be a notable difference. Non-CFA middle/west Africa countries generally exhibit more yearly intervals with a higher median Real GDP Growth Rate. However, it is essential to undertake a comprehensive analysis considering various factors that may influence these growth rates, such as policy frameworks, external shocks, investment climate, and structural characteristics.

GDP, Current Prices comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of GDP, Current Prices

Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is widely recognized as a key indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. It measures the total value of all final goods and services produced within a country over a specific timeframe. When measured in Purchasing Power Parity (PPP), GDP takes into account the relative prices of goods and services across countries by adjusting for differences in the cost of living and inflation rates. By using PPP, GDP provides a more accurate picture of a country’s economic performance, as it allows for comparisons between countries that have different currencies and price levels. This measurement in billions of international dollars further facilitates international comparisons of economic activity, promoting a better understanding of global economic trends and patterns.

Current Account Balance comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Current Account Balance

The Current Account Balance measured as a percentage of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) reflects a country’s economic growth and development by capturing the net result of its trade in goods, services, income, and transfers with the rest of the world. It serves as an essential indicator of a country’s economic health, providing insights into its competitiveness, sustainability, and ability to meet its financial obligations. Positive current account balances signify that a country is exporting more goods and services than it imports, generating income and accumulating financial assets. This can contribute to economic growth and development as it reflects a favorable position in international trade. Conversely, negative current account balances indicate a higher level of imports compared to exports, implying increased reliance on foreign borrowing or asset sales to finance deficits. Such imbalances can signal potential risks to economic stability, as ongoing deficits might lead to debt accumulation or loss of international competitiveness. Thus, monitoring the current account balance as a percentage of GDP enables policymakers and analysts to assess a country’s long-term prospects and make informed decisions to ensure sustained economic growth and development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Current Account Balance

Keynesian economics emphasizes the importance of aggregate demand and domestic investment in driving economic growth. The measure of Overall Fiscal Balance, Excluding Grants as a percentage of GDP captures the extent to which a country’s government revenue covers its expenses, excluding grants received from other countries or international organizations. This indicator holds significant importance in assessing a country’s economic growth and development as it reflects the government’s ability to finance its own activities and manage its fiscal position effectively. A positive overall fiscal balance implies that government revenue exceeds expenses, thus allowing for measures such as infrastructure investments or social welfare programs. On the other hand, a negative balance signifies that the government is relying on borrowing or grants to meet its obligations, potentially indicating a need for fiscal adjustment. By monitoring and analyzing this indicator, policymakers and economists gain insights into a country’s fiscal health and its capacity to sustain long-term economic growth and development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Overall Fiscal Balance, Excluding Grants

A higher Overall Fiscal Balance, Excluding Grants can potentially promote economic growth and development by providing a solid foundation for government expenditures and investments. This enables the funding of critical infrastructure projects, social welfare programs, and public services that contribute to economic activity and human development. However, it is essential to consider the contextual factors that surround this indicator. Comparatively, CFA franc zone countries, as opposed to non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, have shown a higher median for Overall Fiscal Balance, Excluding Grants from 2004 to 2023. This suggests that the CFA franc zone countries have been relatively more successful in maintaining a fiscal position aligned with their economic growth and development ambitions. Nonetheless, it is important to conduct further analysis, considering various factors such as the effectiveness of government spending, the quality of investments, and the overall economic environment, to gain a comprehensive understanding of the impact of fiscal balances on the growth and development dynamics of both CFA franc zone and non-CFA middle/west Africa countries.

Government Debt comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Government Debt

Government debt measured as a percentage of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is a useful indicator used to assess the fiscal health and economic growth of a country. This metric reflects the extent to which a government has accumulated debt relative to its economic output. A higher government debt-to-GDP ratio can imply that a significant portion of the government’s revenues is being utilized to service its debt obligations, potentially crowding out investment in other areas. It is generally believed that excessive levels of government debt can hinder economic development by limiting access to capital and increasing borrowing costs, thereby jeopardizing long-term growth prospects. Consequently, monitoring government debt as a percentage of GDP enables policymakers and economists to evaluate a country’s fiscal sustainability and make informed decisions regarding fiscal policy and debt management.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Government Debt

Higher government debt can indeed promote economic growth and development, as advocated by Keynesian economists. Increased government spending, financed by debt, can stimulate aggregate demand and generate multiplier effects that boost economic output. Moreover, in non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, where the median government debt-to-GDP ratio has been higher than in the CFA franc zone countries between 2004 and 2023, this could imply a higher level of public investment and government intervention aimed at driving economic growth. However, it is crucial to analyze the quality and efficiency of government spending, as well as debt sustainability, to ensure that the increased debt translates into productive investments and does not lead to macroeconomic instability or long-term unsustainability.

External Current Account, Incl.grants comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of External Current Account, Incl.grants

The external current account, including grants and measured as a percentage of GDP, plays a crucial role as an indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. This concept captures the net balance of a nation’s international transactions, encompassing exports and imports of goods and services, income from investments, and unilateral transfers. A positive current account indicates that a country is exporting more than it imports, thus generating income and accumulating financial resources. It signifies a healthy and robust economy, fostering growth and development by providing funds for investments, infrastructure development, and reducing external debt burdens. Conversely, a negative current account suggests that a country is importing more than it exports, resulting in a drain of resources and potentially hampering economic growth. Monitoring and managing the external current account is essential for policymakers as it helps in formulating effective strategies, such as promoting exports, attracting foreign investments, or implementing fiscal and monetary policies, to balance the current account and foster sustainable economic development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator External Current Account, Incl.grants

A higher External Current Account, including grants, can potentially promote economic growth and development. This is because a positive current account balance, indicating that a country is exporting more than it is importing, implies a surplus of resources that can be allocated towards productive investments, infrastructure development, and reducing external debt burdens. A higher current account balance reflects a favorable trade balance and increased export competitiveness, which can stimulate domestic industries, create employment opportunities, and attract foreign investments. It also provides room for a country to accumulate foreign reserves, enhancing financial stability and resilience.

Comparatively, analyzing the periods from 2004 to 2023, CFA franc zone countries have exhibited more intervals with a higher median External Current Account, including grants, than non-CFA middle/west African countries. This difference indicates that CFA franc zone countries, with their fixed exchange rate system tied to the euro and monetary policy managed by the CFA franc zone arrangements, may have enjoyed certain advantages. These advantages could include increased economic stability, improved access to international markets, and stronger alignment with global financial flows. Non-CFA middle/west African countries, on the other hand, may have faced challenges related to exchange rate fluctuations, higher dependency on imports, and limited market access. However, it is important to conduct a more detailed analysis taking into account various factors like economic policies, political stability, and structural characteristics to fully understand the dynamics and implications of the External Current Account, including grants, in both groups of countries.

Hence, monitoring and managing trade balance is of utmost importance for policymakers, as it reflects a nation’s competitiveness, productivity, and ability to sustain economic development.

Real Effective Exchange Rates comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Real Effective Exchange Rates

The concept of Real Effective Exchange Rates (REER) measured in Annual Average Index, 2010 = 100 presents a valuable indicator for assessing a country’s economic growth and development. REER reflects the overall strength or weakness of a nation’s currency in relation to a basket of other currencies, adjusted for inflation. By considering both bilateral exchange rates and inflation differentials, this measure offers a comprehensive perspective on a country’s international competitiveness. A higher REER indicates an appreciation in the currency’s value, implying a potential decline in exports and reduced competitiveness in the global market, while a lower REER signals depreciation, potentially leading to increased export competitiveness. Consequently, monitoring and analyzing REER can help policymakers identify economic imbalances and make informed decisions to promote sustainable growth and development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Real Effective Exchange Rates

A higher Real Effective Exchange Rate (REER) does not necessarily promote economic growth and development, from a Keynesian perspective. While an appreciation in the currency’s value may reduce import costs and inflation in the short term, it can also harm export competitiveness and hinder economic growth in the long run. In analyzing the REER of non-CFA middle/west Africa countries compared to CFA franc zone countries from 2004 to 2022, a concise comparative insight emerges. Non-CFA middle/west Africa countries had a higher median of REER yearly intervals, indicating relatively higher degrees of exchange rate volatility. This suggests that these countries faced greater challenges in maintaining export competitiveness, which can have implications for their economic growth and development.

Nominal Effective Exchange Rates comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Nominal Effective Exchange Rates

Nominal Effective Exchange Rate (NEER) measures the value of a country’s currency relative to a weighted average of other currencies, reflecting its competitiveness in international trade. The NEER, calculated using an Annual Average Index with a base year of 2010, indicates the relative changes in a country’s trade-weighted exchange rate over time. A higher NEER signifies an appreciation in the country’s currency, potentially leading to a decrease in import prices and an increase in export competitiveness. This can support economic growth and development by encouraging domestic industries and attracting foreign investment. Conversely, a lower NEER suggests a depreciation in the country’s currency, which can stimulate domestic demand and boost tourism. Monitoring NEER helps policymakers assess the competitiveness of a country’s exports, manage macroeconomic policies effectively, and make informed decisions to sustain economic growth and development.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Nominal Effective Exchange Rates

A higher Nominal Effective Exchange Rate (NEER) can potentially promote economic growth and development. With a higher NEER, countries in the CFA franc zone may experience increased competitiveness in international trade, as it reflects an appreciation in their currencies. This appreciation can lead to lower import prices and increased export competitiveness, thus stimulating economic growth. Comparatively, non-CFA middle/west Africa countries may face challenges as their currencies tend to be weaker and more volatile. This can make their exports relatively more expensive and hinder their economic growth. Therefore, the higher median NEER observed in CFA franc zone countries from 2004 to 2022 suggests that these countries may have had more favorable conditions for economic growth and development compared to their non-CFA middle/west Africa counterparts.

A higher debt to GDP ratio signifies a greater financial strain on the economy, which can impede growth and development by reducing the government’s fiscal space and increasing the risk of default. Terms Of Trade comparison between African CFA Zone Countries to Non-CFA Middle Africa and Western Africa Countries

Definition of Terms Of Trade

The concept of Terms of Trade, measured in Index with a base year of 2010 set at 100, carries significant importance as an indicator of a country’s economic growth and development. Terms of Trade refer to the ratio at which a country can exchange its exports for imports. A favorable Terms of Trade indicates that a country can acquire a larger quantity of imports in exchange for a given quantity of exports, resulting in increased welfare. Conversely, when the Terms of Trade worsen, a country requires a higher volume of exports to obtain the same level of imports, which can have adverse implications for economic development. Therefore, measuring Terms of Trade through an index allows for a comprehensive analysis of a country’s economic progress and its ability to engage in favorable trade relationships.

Comparing Median Intervals for indicator Terms Of Trade

A higher Terms of Trade can potentially promote economic growth and development. Favorable Terms of Trade imply that a country receives a greater value of imports for a given amount of exports, which can lead to increased domestic consumption, investment, and overall economic activity. In the case of comparing CFA franc zone countries to non-CFA middle/west Africa countries, it can be observed that CFA franc zone countries exhibited more yearly intervals with a higher median Terms of Trade from 2004 to 2023. This suggests that, on average, CFA franc zone countries had a relatively greater ability to exchange their exports for imports compared to non-CFA middle/west Africa countries during this period. Such a comparative insight implies that CFA franc zone countries may have had an advantage in terms of economic growth and development due to more favorable Terms of Trade.
